paragraphs.title: [Function] Cleaning and organize data
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

def initData():
    global dfAll, df
    
    allcols = ['price','accommodates','bedrooms','beds','district','room_type',\
               'cancellation_policy','instant_bookable','reviews_per_month','number_of_reviews',\
               'availability_30','review_scores_rating', 'cultural_organizations', 'incidents']

    #select the new data
    df = dfAll.select(allcols).toPandas()

    # clean the data
    # first fixup 'reviews_per_month' where there are no reviews
    df['reviews_per_month'].fillna(0, inplace=True)

    # just drop rows with bad/weird values
    # (we could do more here)
    df = df[df.bedrooms != 0]
    df = df[df.beds != 0]
    df = df[df.price != 0]
    df = df.dropna(axis=0)

    #convert the wrong data
    df['price'] = df['price'].replace('[\$,)]','', regex=True).replace('[(]','-', regex=True).astype(float)

    df['reviews_per_month'] = df['reviews_per_month'].replace('[\$,)]','', regex=True)\
                .replace('[(]','-', regex=True).astype(float)

paragraphs.title: [Function] Handling Categorical Variables
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

def handleCategoricalVariables():
    #df = df[df.bedrooms == 1]
    global alldata, df
    
    # get feature encoding for categorical variables
    district_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df.district)
    room_type_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df.room_type)
    cancellation_policy_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df.cancellation_policy)

    # convert boolean column to a single boolean value indicating whether this listing has instant booking available
    instant_bookable_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df.instant_bookable, prefix="instant")
    instant_bookable_dummies = instant_bookable_dummies.drop('instant_f', axis=1)

    # replace the old columns with our new one-hot encoded ones
    alldata = pd.concat((df.drop(['district', \
                            'room_type', \
                            'cancellation_policy', \
                            'instant_bookable'], axis=1), \
        district_dummies.astype(int), \
        room_type_dummies.astype(int), \
        cancellation_policy_dummies.astype(int), instant_bookable_dummies.astype(int)), \
        axis=1)

    k_wssse = []

    for k in k_values:
        #número de cluster aleatório

paragraphs.title: [Function] Dividing the data into training and testing subsets
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

def initTrainingTestingSubsets(colname):
    handleCategoricalVariables()
    
    global X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, alldata
    
    # We set random_state=1 to guarantee that the split will be always the same for reproducible results drop what will be analysed
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(alldata.drop([colname], axis=1), alldata[colname], test_size=0.2, random_state=1)

    print("Train set size: %d" % X_train.shape[0])
    print("Test set size: %d" % X_test.shape[0])

paragraphs.title: [Function] Init Linear Models
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

def initLinearModels():
    global models, model_labels, model_errors
    models = [ linear_model.LinearRegression(), linear_model.Ridge(), linear_model.Lasso(), linear_model.ElasticNet(),
        linear_model.BayesianRidge(), linear_model.OrthogonalMatchingPursuit() ]

    model_labels = np.array(['Linear', 'Ridge', 'Lasso', 'ElasticNet', 'BayesRidge', 'OMP'])
    model_errors = np.array([])

paragraphs.title: [Function] Run Linear Models
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

def runLinearModels(colname, log_bool=None):

    initLinearModels()
    initTrainingTestingSubsets(colname)
    global models, model_labels, model_errors
    
    for model in models:
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        if not log_bool:
            model_err = metrics.median_absolute_error(y_test, model.predict(X_test))
            model_errors = np.append(model_errors, model_err)
        else:
            model_err = metrics.median_absolute_error(np.exp(y_test), np.exp(model.predict(X_test)))
            model_errors = np.append(model_errors, model_err)

    pltMedianAbsoluteError(model_labels, model_errors, colname)

paragraphs.title: [Function] Plot Median Absolute Error
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
def pltMedianAbsoluteError(model_labels, model_errors, colname):
    model_position = np.arange(model_errors.shape[0])
    models_sorted = np.argsort(model_errors)
    
    for i, model in enumerate(model_labels):
        print 'Model {} Results: {}'.format(model_labels[i], model_errors[i])
        
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    plt.bar(model_position, model_errors[models_sorted], align='center')
    plt.xticks(model_position, model_labels[models_sorted])
    plt.xlabel('Estimator')
    plt.ylabel('Median Absolute Error')
    plt.savefig("data/NewYork/img/median_absolute_error_{}.pdf".format(colname))

paragraphs.title: [Function] GradientBoostingRegressor + Plot error of boosting
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

def runGradientBoostingRegressor(colname):
    initTrainingTestingSubsets(colname)
    global X_train, y_train, clf
    
    n_est = 300
    tuned_parameters = {"n_estimators": [ n_est ], "max_depth" : [ 4 ], "learning_rate": [ 0.01 ], "min_samples_split" : [ 2], "loss" : [ 'ls', 'lad' ]}

    #estimator
    estimator = ensemble.GradientBoostingRegressor()
    
    clf = GridSearchCV(estimator, cv=3, param_grid=tuned_parameters, scoring='neg_median_absolute_error')
    preds = clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    best = clf.best_estimator_
    
    #print "Best estimator"
    #print best
    #print "Best parameters"
    #print clf.best_params_

    print "Median Absolute Error of $ {}".format(round(abs(clf.best_score_),2))
    
    test_score = np.zeros(n_est, dtype=np.float64)

    train_score = best.train_score_
    for i, y_pred in enumerate(best.staged_predict(X_test)):
        test_score[i] = best.loss_(y_test, y_pred)

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6), dpi=100)
    plt.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=16)
    #plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(np.arange(n_est), train_score, 'darkblue', label='Training Set Error')
    plt.plot(np.arange(n_est), test_score, 'red', label='Test Set Error')
    plt.legend(loc='upper right', prop={'size':16})
    plt.xlabel('Boosting Iterations', fontsize=16)
    plt.ylabel('Least Absolute Deviation', fontsize=16)
    plt.savefig("data/NewYork/img/gradient_boosting_regressor_{}.pdf".format(colname))

paragraphs.title: [Function] Plot Feature Importance from GridSearchCV
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

def plotFeatureImportanceGridSearchCV(colname):
    feature_importance = clf.best_estimator_.feature_importances_
    # make importances relative to max importance
    feature_importance = 100.0 * (feature_importance / feature_importance.max())
    sorted_idx = np.argsort(feature_importance)
    pos = np.arange(sorted_idx.shape[0]) + .5
    pvals = feature_importance[sorted_idx]
    pcols = X_train.columns[sorted_idx]
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,12), dpi=100)
    plt.barh(pos, pvals, align='center')
    plt.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=12)
    plt.yticks(pos, pcols)
    plt.xlabel('Relative Importance', fontsize=16)
    plt.title('Variable Importance', fontsize=16)
    plt.savefig("data/NewYork/img/feature_importance_gridSearchCV_{}.pdf".format(colname))

def assembleFeatureVectors(position):

    alldataDF = assembler.transform(alldataDF.dropna())

%md
## Linear Models

For this nalaysis using linear models the data was divided into train and test subsets. For that we are going to use [scikit-learn](http://scikit-learn.org/). Scikit-learn is a Python module for machine learning with many other utilities to deal with common tasks in machine learning. We have set `random_state = 1` in `train_test_split` function to guarantee that the split will be always the same for reproducible results.

Analisando o gŕáfico **Bedrooms distribution** podemos observar que aproximadamente 82% dos dados são para listagens de um quarto, então é o tipo de unidade para qual temos mais amostras. Focalizando nossa regressão em um único tipo de unidade, nosso modelo será melhor, pois há menos a descobrir sobre as interações complexas com outras características (como se a unidade é compartilhada, privada ou tem uma sala privada). Para fazer previsões para unidades maiores, uma maneira seria desenvolver modelos separados para cada um dos diferentes tamanhos (2, 3, 4 quartos, etc.), ou fazer algum agrupamento para ver se é melhor particionar os dados de alguma outra maneira.

Para a análise a predição do preço, de modo a avaliar o comportamento do machine learning, será utilizado dados com todos os quartos, 1 e 2 quartos.

%md

Em seguida, vamos tentar um método conjunto para ver se podemos obter melhores resultados. O lado positivo é que provavelmente obteremos uma pontuação melhor, e a desvantagem é que os métodos de conjunto têm uma variedade desconcertante de hiperparâmetros que devem ser ajustados, cada um dos quais pode afetar nosso modelo e requer alguma experimentação para acertar. A maneira comum de abordar isso é usar uma exaustiva "grid search" que simplesmente tenta todas as combinações de parâmetros fornecidas e usa cross-validation para encontrar o melhor. Scikit-learn fornece a função muito útil GridSearchCV para esta finalidade.

A compensação de usar GridSearchCV é que a busca exaustiva e cross-validation pode levar um monte de CPU e tempo. É aqui que podemos utilizar o Spark para distribuir a pesquisa a mais máquinas e núcleos, permitindo-nos testar mais combinações mais rapidamente. 

The grid search provided by **GridSearchCV** exhaustively generates candidates from a grid of parameter values specified with the `param_grid` parameter. For instance, the following `param_grid`:
  

Gradient Tree Boosting or Gradient Boosted Regression Trees (GBRT) is a generalization of boosting to arbitrary differentiable loss functions. GBRT is an accurate and effective off-the-shelf procedure that can be used for both regression and classification problems. Gradient Tree Boosting models are used in a variety of areas including Web search ranking and ecology.


`n_estimators = 300`
`max_depth = 4`
`learning_rate = 0.01`
`min_samples_split = 2`
`loss = ls / lad`
`scoring = neg_median_absolute_error`
`cv = 3`    
`Estimator = GradientBoostingRegressor`  


The advantages of GBRT are:
* Natural handling of data of mixed type (= heterogeneous features)
* Predictive power
* Robustness to outliers in output space (via robust loss functions)

The disadvantages of GBRT are:
* Scalability, due to the sequential nature of boosting it can hardly be parallelized.


[Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gradient_boosting)

%md
O resultado dessa tentativa é um erro médio de $ 24

Já, parece que estamos fazendo melhor com GradientBoostingRegressor do que estávamos com qualquer uma das tentativas anteriores. Sem fazer qualquer ajuste, o erro mediano é cerca de 20% menor que o melhor erro do grupo anterior (com Lasso ()). 

Vamos obter uma medida rápida de como o erro é afetado por cada rodada de reforço, para que possamos ver se jogar mais iterações no problema vai ajudar.
Parece que começa a convergir em cerca de 200-250 iterações, mas ainda está se beneficiando de mais iterações, então poderíamos aumentar as iterações para 500 sem pensar muito.

No próximo gráfico observamos quais características são mais influentes na previsão do preço. 

Isso nos mostra uma pontuação relativa da importância de cada recurso em relação ao recurso com maior importância.

É claro que algumas das variáveis têm mais influência do que outras, e os resultados aqui são um pouco intuitivos. O recurso mais influente é o atributo **Entire home/apt**; Isso indica se ou não a unidade é compartilhada com outras pessoas, e tem o maior efeito na fixação do preço. Nós provavelmente esperaríamos que esse recurso ficasse alto na lista, e poderia ser ainda mais alto. paragraphs.title: Unsupervised Learning: K-Means Clustering
paragraphs.text:
%md

#### Unsupervised Learning

"Unsupervised learning is the machine learning task of inferring a function to describe hidden structure from unlabeled data. Since the examples given to the learner are unlabeled, there is no error or reward signal to evaluate a potential solution. This distinguishes unsupervised learning from supervised learning and reinforcement learning." - [wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unsupervised_learning)

#### K-Means Clustering

K-Means is one of the most commonly used clustering algorithms that clusters the data points into a predefined number of clusters. (See [Spark docs](http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/ml-clustering.html) for more info.)

We will use Spark ML API to generate a K-Means model using the Spark ML KMeans class. 

KMeans is implemented as an Estimator and generates a KMeansModel as the base model.

Note that the data points for the training are hardcoded in the example below. Before you run the K-Means sample code, try to guess what the two cluster centers should be based on the training data.

paragraphs.title: Decision Trees
paragraphs.text:
%md

Decision trees and their ensembles are popular methods for the machine learning tasks of classification and regression. Decision trees are widely used since they are easy to interpret, handle categorical features, extend to the multiclass classification setting, do not require feature scaling, and are able to capture non-linearities and feature interactions. Tree ensemble algorithms such as random forests and boosting are among the top performers for classification and regression tasks.

The spark.ml implementation supports decision trees for binary and multiclass classification and for regression, using both continuous and categorical features. The implementation partitions data by rows, allowing distributed training with millions or even billions of instances. ([See docs](http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/ml-classification-regression.html#decision-trees) for more info.)

Make sure to checkout **[this](http://www.r2d3.us/visual-intro-to-machine-learning-part-1/)** great introduction to Visual Machine Learning to get an intuitive feel for the *ideas* behind Decision Tree classification.

paragraphs.title: Random Forest
paragraphs.text:
%md

As a fan of greedy algorithm, I would like to start with *random forest* algorithm.

What is the idea of **Random Forest**? 

To put it simple, averaging a set of observations reduces variance. Hence a natural way to reduce the variance and hence increase the prediction accuracy of a decision tree model is to take training sets repeatedly from the population, build a separate tree model using each training set, and average the resulting predictions [1]. This is the idea of **bagging** (**B**ootstrap **agg**regat**ing**). 

Then we may need to subset the predictors. That is, in each split of one tree model, we don't use all the features we have. You may ask WHY since this seems like a 'waste' of resources we have. But let's suppose that there is a very strong predictor in the data, then in the models we produced, most of them will use that strong predictor in the top split and all of these decision trees will look similar, i.e., they're highly correlated. This may effect the reduction in variance and worsen the result. [1] This is why we only use randomly selected features in each split of the tree models. 

This is just the idea of **random forest**. Simple, straitforward, and elegant at the same time.

## Conclusion

By history, we know that women had priority to be saved and, as a matter of fact, this feature is the most important in both the logistic regression and the random forest. Another important feature is the age, in the case of logistic regression, it is not as important as in the random forest. That's probably why random forest performed better than logistic regression, but not by much. So, we can conclude that a simple model is not always a bad model.
